n I Opened My Mouth?” Asian American Indie Rock and the Middling Noise of Racialization -- t15 Winning the Bee: South Asians, Spelling Bee Competitions, and American Racial Branding -- t16 The Blood Sport of Cooking: On Asian American Chefs and Television -- tPart IV Migration and Transnational Popular Culture -- t17 Curry as Code: Food, Race, and Technology -- t18 Bollywood’s 9/11 Terrorism and Muslim Masculinities in Popular Hindi Cinema -- t19 Hybrid Hallyu: The African American Music Tradition in K-Pop -- t20 Transnational Beauty Circuits: Asian American Women, Technology, and Circle Contact Lenses -- t21 Making Whales out of Peacocks: Virtual Fashion and Asian Female Factory Hands -- t22 Failed Returns: The Queer Balikbayan in R. Zamora Linmark’s Leche and Gil Portes’s Miguel/Michelle -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA toolkit for understanding how Asian Americans influence, consume and are reflected by mainstream media. Asian Americans have long been the subject and object of popular culture in the U.S. The rapid circulation of cultural flashpoints-such as the American obsession with K-pop sensations, Bollywood dance moves, and sriracha hot sauce-have opened up new ways of understanding how the categories of “Asian” and “Asian American” are counterbalanced within global popular culture. Located at the crossroads of these global and national expressions, Global Asian American Popular Cultures highlights new approaches to modern culture, with essays that explore everything from music, film, and television to comics, fashion, food, and sports. As new digital technologies and cross-media convergence have expanded exchanges of transnational culture, Asian American popular culture emerges as a crucial site for understanding how communities share information and how the meanings of mainstream culture shift with technologies and newly mobile sensibilities. Asian American popular culture is also at the crux of global and national trends in media studies, collapsing boundaries and acting as a lens to view the ebbs and flows of transnational influences on global and American cultures. Offering new and critical analyses of popular cultures that account for emerging textual fields, global producers, technologies of distribution, and trans-medial circulation, this ground-breaking collectionexplores the mainstream and the margins of popular culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aAfzal, Ahmed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Crystal S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArnaldo, Constancio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAugust, Timothy K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDave, Shilpa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavé, Shilpa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiaz, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFojas, Camilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIshii, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Julia H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLopez, Lori Kido, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaeda, Daryl Joji, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMallapragada, Madhavi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMisri, Deepti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNg, Konrad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aN